GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
38. Transportation Quantity Adjustment Mechanism
38.1 Purpose of Mechanism. Transporter shall establish a Transportation Quantity Adjustment Mechanism and shall, if permitted by the provisions of the mechanism, file annually to adjust Transporter’s prospective Recourse Rates for all transportation services provided pursuant to this F.E.R.C. Gas Tariff.
38.2 Annual Filing Requirement. Each year Transporter shall compare the quantities actually received for Shippers, converted to full rate equivalent quantities, during the previous calendar year to the initial design quantities underlying the Recourse Rates. If the full rate equivalent quantities actually received from Shippers vary from the initial design quantities by more than ten percent (10%), Transporter shall file on or before each April 1 to adjust the Recourse Rates in effect from time to time in accordance with the provisions of this Section 38; provided, however, no such filing shall be made before April 1, 2012. The adjusted Recourse Rates shall be effective as of May 1 of the calendar year in which the filing occurs.
38.3 Calculation of Annual Adjustment. The annual adjustment calculation shall be the total of a current adjustment and a true-up adjustment as provided by this section.
a) Current Adjustment. When the full rate equivalent quantities vary from the initial design quantities by more than ten percent (10%), Transporter shall compute a monthly revenue variance by comparing the actual revenues collected by Month during the previous calendar year, with the revenues designed to be collected by Month. Transporter shall determine the monthly design revenues by assuming collection of the total cost of service in twelve (12) equal installments. Transporter shall calculate interest on the monthly revenue variance using the weighted average cost of debt and equity underlying its initial Recourse Rates. The current annual adjustment shall be calculated as the quotient of (a) the sum of the monthly revenue variances and the accumulated interest and (b) the projected full rate equivalent quantities for the calendar year of the filing.

GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
b) True-Up Adjustment. Starting with the second filing under this mechanism, Transporter shall compare the monthly revenues designed to be collected under the previous year's annual filing with the monthly revenues actually collected during the previous year and shall calculate a true- up adjustment. Transporter shall determine the monthly design revenues by assuming collection in twelve (12) equal installments. Transporter shall calculate interest on the monthly revenue variance using the weighted average cost of debt and equity underlying its initial Recourse Rates. The current annual true-up adjustment shall be calculated as the quotient of (a) the sum of the monthly revenue variances and the accumulated interest and (b) the projected full rate equivalent quantities for the calendar year of the filing.

(b) It is Stingray’s intent that the accounting set forth in Section 36.4(a) hereof shall operate as a true-up mechanism between Stingray’s (1) Eligible Costs and (2) Event Surcharge revenue plus Insurance Recoveries and other recoveries from third parties of Eligible Costs previously included in the Event Surcharge Cost Account.
36.5 CALCULATION OF THE EVENT SURCHARGE
The Event Surcharge shall equal:
(1) The latest available balance in the Event Surcharge Cost Account, divided by
(2) The projected total system throughput (unadjusted for any rate discounting) for the 12-Month period beginning on the proposed effective date of the applicable Event Surcharge.
(b) In calculation of the Event Surcharge in each separate filing pursuant to Section 36.3(a) hereof, the collection of any Eligible Costs included for recovery in such filing shall be amortized over a 36 Month period; provided, however, that if the Event Surcharge as calculated in accordance with the foregoing is less than $0.005/Dth, Stingray may amortize the amount in the Event Surcharge Cost Account over 12 Months.
(c) To the extent that any portion of the Event Surcharge Cost Account remains uncollected at the end of the 36 Month amortization period, the foregone revenue plus carrying costs at the FERC-prescribed interest rate may be collected by Stingray in a subsequent period.
(d) If the amount in the Event Surcharge Cost Account is less than $100,000 (either negative or positive), Stingray may, upon at least thirty (30) Days prior notice to the Commission, reduce the Event Surcharge to $0.00/Dth and refund to or bill Shippers the amount in the Event Surcharge Cost Account in the invoice for the Month following the date the Event Surcharge is reduced to $0.00/Dth based on the actual quantities received by Stingray for each Shipper during such Month.
